          "body": "Verse 6 is one of the most anatomically specific verses in the Old Testament prophets. The Servant gave his back to those who struck him, his cheeks to those who plucked out the beard, and did not cover his face from humiliation and spitting. Three distinct abuses, three distinct body parts, total absence of self-protection. The vocabulary of the verse is the vocabulary of deep honor-shame transgression in the ancient Near Eastern world: beard-plucking was the most extreme form of personal humiliation (cf. 2 Samuel 10:4); spitting on the face was a legal-ceremonial insult (Numbers 12:14; Deuteronomy 25:9). The Servant does not merely endure these things — he *gives* his back, *gives* his cheeks. The verbs are volitional. He is not a passive victim but an active offerer of himself to the indignity. The New Testament quotation of 50:6 in the Passion narratives (Matthew 26:67; 27:26, 30; Mark 14:65; 15:19; John 18:22; 19:1, 3) makes the Servant's identity explicit for the Christian reader: the one who gave his face to the spittle is Jesus of Nazareth in the Praetorium and the courtyard of the high priest."
