          "body": "Verse 7 names the source of the Servant's capacity to absorb 50:6 without breaking: 'The Lord God helps Me, therefore I am not disgraced; therefore I have set My face like flint.' The grammar is irreversible — divine help produces the 'therefore' of non-disgrace, which produces the 'therefore' of set-face resolution. The metaphor of flint (*challamish*) is the hardest naturally occurring stone in the ancient Near Eastern environment, used for cutting tools precisely because it cannot be ground down. But the Servant's flint-face is not stoic self-hardening; it is entirely derivative of 'the Lord God helps Me.' He then issues a forensic challenge in the language of Israel's covenant law court (50:8-9): 'Who will contend with Me? ... Who has a case against Me? ... Who condemns Me?' The expected answer is silence — there is no case. Paul hears this passage in Romans 8:33-34 and transposes it to the believer's standing in Christ: 'Who will bring a charge against God's elect? God is the one who justifies.' The Servant's courtroom vindication becomes the template for the church's standing in the last day."
