          "body": "The chapter's final two verses constitute a double pastoral address that forces the reader off the fence. The first address (50:10) is to 'the one among you who fears the LORD, who obeys the voice of His Servant' — that is, the genuine God-fearer — who nevertheless 'walks in darkness and has no light.' This is not the darkness of moral sin but the darkness of providential obscurity: the believer whose circumstances are unresolved, whose prayers seem unanswered, whose suffering has not yet yielded to light. The counsel is not explanation but trust: 'Let him trust in the name of the LORD and rely on his God.' The name of the LORD is the divine self-disclosure — His covenant character, His record of faithfulness. The verb *shaan* (rely, lean) suggests the posture of one leaning weight on a support they did not build. The second address (50:11) is the sharpest warning in the chapter, aimed at those who 'kindle a fire' and 'walk in the light of your fire.' These are not pagans or apostates — they are people in proximity to the God-fearing community (the same 'you' as 50:10) who, unable to endure the darkness of trust, have manufactured their own illumination: self-confidence, self-sufficient strategies, autonomous certainty about their path. The irony is devastating: the fire they use to see by becomes the instrument of their torment. From God's hand — the same hand whose shortness He denied in 50:2 — comes the torment that follows self-lit walking."
